description: From Middle English enselen, inselen, inseilen, from Old English inseġlian (“to place a seal on”), from Proto-West Germanic *insigilōn (compare Old High German insigilōn, insigilen, Old Norse innsigla (“to seal”)), from Latin insigilāre; merged with and reinforced by Old French enseeler, from the same Latin source. Equivalent to en- +‎ seal.

verbs.description: enseal (third-person singular simple present enseals, present participle ensealing, simple past and past participle ensealed)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To mark as with a seal.
